# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: keras
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In machine learning, a **neural network** (**NN**) or **neural net**, is a computational model inspired by the structure and functions of biological neural networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A neural network consists of connected units or nodes called *artificial neurons*, which loosely model the neurons in the brain.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neuron models that mimic biological neurons more closely have also been recently investigated and shown to significantly improve performance.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are connected by *edges*, which model the synapses in the brain.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each artificial neuron receives signals from connected neurons, then processes them and sends a signal to other connected neurons.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The "signal" is a real number, and the output of each neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the totality of its inputs, called the *activation function*.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The strength of the signal at each connection is determined by a *weight*, which adjusts as part of the training process.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Groups of neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each layer performs a transformation on its inputs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the *input layer*) to the last layer (the *output layer*), typically passing through multiple intermediate layers (*hidden layers*).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least two hidden layers.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are capable of learning sophisticated hierarchical representations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training neural networks is a compute-intensive process, accelerated by the use of graphics processing units (GPUs), and large datasets.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Architectural innovations such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) significantly improved performance in computer vision tasks, while recurrent neural networks (RNNs) enabled modeling of sequential data such as speech and time-series information.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformer architectures introduced attention mechanisms that allow neural networks to model long-range dependencies in data and have the basis of large language models.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks are used for a myriad of tasks including chatbots, large-scale text, image, and video generation, and robotics.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are based on statistics developed over 200 years ago.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest kind of feedforward neural network (FNN) is a linear network, which consists of a single layer of output nodes with linear activation functions; the inputs are fed directly to the outputs via weights.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The sum of the products of the weights and the inputs is calculated at each node.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The mean squared errors between these calculated outputs and the given target values are minimized by adjusting to the weights.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This technique is the method of least squares or linear regression.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used to find a rough linear fit to a set of points by Legendre (1805) and Gauss (1795) for the prediction of planetary movement.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Computers are based on John von Neumann's model.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They execute explicit lists of instructions with access to memory to record their changing state.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks instead originated from efforts to model information processing in biological systems via connectionism.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unlike the von Neumann model, connectionist computing does not separate memory and processing.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts (1943) considered a non-learning computational model for neural networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This model paved the way for research to split into one branch focused on biological processes and another focused on artificial intelligence.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] McCulloch and Pitts also developed mathematical models of artificial neurons capable of representing logical functions.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb proposed a learning hypothesis based on neural plasticity that became known as Hebbian learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used in many early neural network experiments, such as Rosenblatt's perceptron and the Hopfield network.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Farley and Clark (1954) used computational machines to simulate a Hebbian network.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Other neural networks computational machines were created by Rochester, Holland, Habit and Duda (1956).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1958, psychologist Frank Rosenblatt described the perceptron, one of the first implemented neural networks, funded by the United States Office of Naval Research.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Joseph (1960) mentioned an earlier perceptron-like device by B.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first perceptrons did not have adaptive hidden units.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, Joseph (1960) discussed multilayer that did.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rosenblatt (1962) cited and adopted these ideas, crediting work by H.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, these early efforts did not lead to a working learning algorithm for hidden units, i.e., deep learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The perceptron raised public excitement in neural networks, causing the US government to drastically increase funding.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This contributed to "the Golden Age of AI", fueled by the optimistic claims made by computer scientists regarding the ability of perceptrons to emulate human intelligence.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks were identified as a promising direction for artificial intelligence research in the 1955 proposal for the Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural network models initially faced major limitations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hardware constraints limited network size and training efficiency, while theoretical understanding of learning algorithms remained incomplete.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many models used single-layer perceptrons, which were restricted to solving linearly separable problems.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] These limitations were highlighted in the book *Perceptrons* by Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert, which deflated interest during the late 1960s and 1970s.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fundamental research was conducted on NNs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Valentin Lapa in the Soviet Union (1965).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, generalizing Rosenblatt's perceptron.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, training layer by layer via regression analysis.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Superfluous hidden units were pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The activation functions of the nodes were Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron (MLP) trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student S.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tuning made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the dominant technique for reducing loss (error).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] RelLU is the most common activation function.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nevertheless, research stagnated in the United States after Minsky and Papert (1969), who emphasized that perceptrons were incapable of processing the exclusive-or circuit.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, this insight was irrelevant for the deep networks of Ivakhnenko (1965) and Amari (1967).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1976, transfer learning was introduced.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Interest in neural networks revived during the 1980s because of the novel backpropagation algorithm, which allowed multi-layer neural networks to be trained efficiently by propagating error gradients backward (from output back to input) through network layers.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not describe how to implement this.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Kelley developed a precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1970, Seppo Linnainmaa published the modern form of backpropagation in his master's thesis (1970).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not describe the algorithm).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rumelhart, et al., popularized backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers and weight replication began with the neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's CNN architecture also introduced max pooling, a popular downsampling procedure for CNNs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] CNNs have become an essential tool for computer vision.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNNs to phoneme recognition.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to recognizing individual letters.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al. that classifies hand-written digits, was applied by banks to recognize numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] From 1988 onward, the use of neural networks transformed the field of protein structure prediction, in particular when the first cascading networks were trained on *profiles* (matrices) produced by multiple sequence alignments.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] One source of RNN was statistical mechanics.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari proposed to modify the weights of an Ising model by Hebbian learning rule as a model of associative memory, adding in learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was popularized as the Hopfield network by John Hopfield (1982).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The word "recurrent" is used to describe loop-like structures in anatomy.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1901, Cajal observed "recurrent semicircles" in the cerebellar cortex.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb considered "reverberating circuit" as an explanation for short-term memory.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The McCulloch and Pitts paper (1943) considered neural networks that contain cycles, and noted that the current activity of such networks can be affected by activity indefinitely far in the past.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1982 Crossbar Adaptive Array, a recurrent neural network with an array architecture (rather than a multilayer perceptron architecture), used direct recurrent connections from the output to the supervisor (teaching) inputs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition to computing actions (decisions), it computed internal state evaluations (emotions) of consequence situations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Eliminating the external supervisor, it introduced the self-learning method in neural networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In cognitive psychology, the *American Psychologist* journal in the early 1980s debated the relation between cognition and emotion.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Social psychologist Robert Zajonc in 1980 stated that emotion is computed first and is independent from cognition, while Richard Lazarus in 1982 stated that cognition is computed first and is inseparable from emotion.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was an example of a debate where an RNN contributed to an issue and also addressed cognitive psychology.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990) applied RNN to study cognitive psychology.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep RNNs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed the "neural sequence chunker" or "neural history compressor" which introduced self-supervised pre-training (the "P" in ChatGPT) and neural knowledge distillation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem and proposed recurrent residual connections to solve it.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] He and Schmidhuber introduced long short-term memory (LSTM), which set accuracy records in multiple application domains.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was not the ultimate version of LSTM, which required the forget gate, and was introduced in 1999.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It became the default choice for RNN architecture.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, and others, including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Between 2009 and 2012, NNs began winning prizes in image recognition contests, approaching human performance on various tasks, initially in pattern recognition and handwriting recognition.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2011, *DanNet,* a CNN by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2012, Ng and Dean created a network that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, from training only on unlabeled images.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised pre-training and increased computing power from GPUs and distributed computing allowed the use of larger networks, particularly in image and visual recognition problems, which became known as "deep learning".
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Radial basis function and wavelet networks were introduced in 2013.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] These can be shown to offer best approximation properties and have been applied in nonlinear system identification and classification applications.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) became state of the art in generative modeling from 2014–2018.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] GAN was originally published in 1991 by Schmidhuber, who called it "artificial curiosity": two neural networks contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Excellent image quality was achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Here, the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling thereafter, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "[a] very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2015, training very deep networks advanced with the highway network, published in May, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in December.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] During the 2010s, the seq2seq model was developed, and attention mechanisms were added.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This led to the modern transformer architecture in 2017 in "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It requires computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Schmidhuber's fast weight controller (1992) scales linearly and was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers have increasingly become the model of choice for natural language processing.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many modern large language models such as GPT, Gemini, Grok, DeepSeek, and Qwen use this architecture.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs began as an attempt to replicate the architecture of the brain in the digital realm.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs immediately showed promise for handling non-linear relationships, but encountered obstacles.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models soon reoriented to applying mathematical insights to improve empirical results, at the expense of biological fidelity.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are composed of digital neurons, conceptually derived from biological neurons.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron has one or more numerical inputs and produces a single numerical output.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] An input (e.g., an image) is typically parceled across the set of input neurons (each getting a piece of the image).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron's inputs, weighted by the weights of the connections from each of those inputs are summed.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A bias term is added to this sum.) The result is then passed through a nonlinear activation function to produce the neuron's output.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Small enough outputs may be zeroed out (ignored).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs connect neurons to each other, using the output of some neurons as the input of others, akin to biological axon-synapse-dendrite connections.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network forms a directed, weighted graph.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weights apply to both the graph's the nodes and edges.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nodes are arranged in layers, with the bottom layers directly addressing raw data, while the top layers reveal the final results.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Intermediate layers gradually increase the level of abstraction, so what began as for example, pixels in an image, gradually resolves into things such as object boundaries, and then into real-world objects such as letters and faces.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Single layer and unlayered networks are also used.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Multiple connection patterns have been used.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Traditionally, they are *fully connected*, with every neuron in one layer connecting to every neuron in the next layer.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, in convolutional neural networks, some layers are *convolutional,* meaning each neuron in one layer is connected to a subset of neurons in the previous layer, such as those representing one section of an image.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In most neural networks, the outputs of the neurons in one layer are connected only to neurons in the immediately following layer (directed acyclic graph), meaning information only flows forward from one layer to the next.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are known as feedforward networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In contrast, networks that allow connections between neurons in the same or previous layers are known as recurrent networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training/learning involves adjusting the weights of the network to improve the accuracy of the result.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs typically require vast numbers of sample inputs (far more than biological brains) to achieve a given level of function.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is done by minimizing the observed errors among sample observations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training takes place before a network is deployed, and (unlike brains) does not continue thereafter.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network may be retrained from scratch as more sample data becomes available.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Empirical risk minimization adjusts node and link weights to minimize the difference (empirical risk), between the predicted output and the known values in the training samples.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A defined loss function measures the degree of error.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation spreads the error (adjusts the weights) from the output nodes across the network to the input nodes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The intent is to allow the network to process data that is not included in the training samples.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] As long as the value of the loss function (its cost) continues to decline, the network is continuing to improve.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The function typically produces a statistic whose value is only approximate.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the cost is low, the difference between the output (*e.g.* almost certainly a cat) and the correct answer (a cat) is small.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Most learning models can be viewed as a straightforward application of optimization theory and statistical estimation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning typically ends when additional observations do not usefully reduce the cost.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost typically approaches, but does not reach, 0.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] If no feasible amount of sample data yields a low cost, training is labeled a failure.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] While it is possible to assess a loss function ad hoc, typically it must exhibit desirable properties such as convexity, differentiability, and robustness.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a probabilistic model, the model's posterior probability can be used as an inverse cost (higher values are better).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is a method used to adjust the connection weights to compensate for errors found during learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The error amount is essentially divided among the connections.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Technically, backpropagation calculates the gradient (the derivative) of the loss function associated with a given state with respect to the weights.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weight updates can be done via stochastic gradient descent or other methods, such as *extreme learning machines*, "no-prop" networks, training without backtracking, "weightless" networks, and non-connectionist neural networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A hyperparameter is a parameter defining any configurable part of the network and learning process whose value is set prior to training.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Examples of hyperparameters include learning rate, sample batch size, number of nodes and layers, etc .
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The performance of a neural network is strongly influenced by hyperparameter choices, and thus may be adjusted during training (typically between training runs), a process called hyperparameter tuning or hyperparameter optimization.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning rate defines the size of the corrective steps that the model takes to adjust for errors in each observation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A high learning rate shortens training time, but with lower ultimate accuracy, while a lower learning rate takes longer, but with the potential for greater accuracy.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Optimizations such as quickprop are primarily aimed at accelerating learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In order to avoid oscillations such as connection weights that cycle between high and low values, and to improve the rate of convergence, refinements use an adaptive learning rate that increases or decreases as appropriate.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The concept of momentum allows the balance between the gradient and the previous change to be weighted such that the weight adjustment depends to some degree on the previous change.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A momentum close to 0 emphasizes the gradient, while a value close to 1 emphasizes the last change.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Machine learning has involved a variety of approaches to training models, including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, reinforcement learning, and self-supervised learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning pairs inputs and desired outputs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning task is to produce the desired output for each input.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In this case, the cost is related to eliminating incorrect outputs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A commonly used cost is the mean-squared error, which tries to minimize the average squared error between the network's output and the desired output.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Tasks suited for supervised learning include pattern recognition (classification) and regression (function approximation).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning is applicable to sequential data (e.g., for handwriting, speech and gesture recognition).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This can be thought of as learning with a "teacher", in the form of a function that provides continuous feedback.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In unsupervised learning, input data is given along with the cost function for the data $\textstyle x$ and the output, without an "answer sheet".
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function is dependent on the task (the model domain) and reflects *a priori* assumptions (implicit model properties, its parameters and the observed variables).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, the model $\textstyle f(x)=a$ treats $\textstyle a$ is a constant and the cost $\textstyle C=E[(x-f(x))^{2}]$ .
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Minimizing this cost produces a value of $\textstyle a$ that is equal to the mean of the data.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function can be much more complicated.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its form depends on the application: for example, in compression it could be related to the mutual information between $\textstyle x$ and $\textstyle f(x)$ , whereas in statistical modeling, it could be related to the posterior probability (in both examples, those quantities are maximized).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised learning is typically applied to estimation problems; applications include clustering, the estimation of statistical distributions, compression, and filtering.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning (SSL) is a paradigm in machine learning where a model is trained on a task using the data itself to generate supervisory signals, rather than relying on externally-provided labels.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the context of neural networks, self-supervised learning aims to leverage inherent structures or relationships within the input data to create meaningful training signals.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] SSL tasks are designed so that solving them requires capturing essential features or relationships in the data.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The input data is typically augmented or transformed in a way that creates pairs of related samples, where one sample serves as the input, and the other is used to formulate the supervisory signal.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This augmentation can involve introducing noise, cropping, rotation, or other transformations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning more closely imitates the way humans learn to classify objects.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In applications such as playing video games, an actor takes a string of actions, receiving a generally unpredictable response from the environment (the game) after each one.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The goal is to win the game (get the highest score).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reinforcement learning, the aim is to weight the network to increase the score.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] After each action the game generates an observation and an instantaneous cost, according to its rules.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The rules and the long-term cost can only be estimated.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] At any juncture, the agent decides whether to explore new actions to uncover their costs or to exploit prior learning to proceed more quickly.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Formally, the environment is modeled as a Markov decision process (MDP) with states $\textstyle {s_{1},...,s_{n}}\in S$ and actions $\textstyle {a_{1},...,a_{m}}\in A$ .
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Taken together, the two define a Markov chain (MC).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The aim is to discover the lowest-cost MC.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-learning was introduced in 1982 along with a *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA) NN that could teach itself.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation s, and only one output, action (or behavior) a.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It has neither external advice input nor external reinforcement from the environment.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about encountered situations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, its behavioral environment, and its genetic environment, from which it receives initial emotions (only once) about to be encountered situations in the behavioral environment.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Having received the genome vector (species vector) from the genetic environment, the CAA will learn a goal-seeking behavior, in the behavioral environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution can create NN topologies and weights using evolutionary computation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is competitive with gradient descent approaches.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution may be less prone to get caught in "dead ends".
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Topological deep learning, introduced in 2017, integrates topology with deep neural networks to address high-order data.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Initially rooted in algebraic topology, TDL evolved into a versatile framework incorporating tools from mathematical disciplines such as differential topology and geometric topology.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a Bayesian framework, a distribution over the set of allowed models is chosen to minimize cost.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Evolutionary methods, gene expression programming, simulated annealing, expectation–maximization, non-parametric methods and particle swarm optimization are other learning algorithms.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Convergent recursion is a learning algorithm for cerebellar model articulation controller (CMAC) neural networks.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning can be either stochastic or batch.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning creates a weight adjustment for each sample.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In batch learning, weights are adjusted based on a batch of inputs, accumulating errors over the batch.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning introduces "noise" into the process, using the local gradient calculated from one data point; this reduces the chance of the network getting stuck in local minima.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, batch learning typically yields a faster, more stable descent to a local minimum, since each update is performed in the direction of the batch's average error.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A common compromise is to use "mini-batches", small batches with samples in each batch selected stochastically from the entire data set.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Types of neural networks (NN) include a family of techniques.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest types have static components, including number of units, number of layers, unit weights and topology.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types allow/require learning to be "supervised" by the operator, while others operate independently.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types operate purely in hardware, while others are purely software and run on general purpose computers.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The choice of model depends on the data and the application.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models that work well with textual data are typically not the best choice for image data, etc.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] An important element is which training/learning the model uses.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural architecture search (NAS) uses machine learning to automate NN design.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NAS has yielded networks that compare well with hand-designed systems.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The basic algorithm is to propose a candidate model, evaluate it against a dataset, and use the results as feedback to teach the NAS network.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Efforts include AutoML and AutoKeras. scikit-learn library provides functions to help with building a deep network from scratch.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are design choices (they are not learned).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The multilayer perceptron is a universal function approximator, as proven by the universal approximation theorem.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the proof does not specify the number of neurons required, the network topology, the weights or the learning parameters.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A recurrent architecture with rational-valued weights (as opposed to full precision real number-valued weights) has the power of a universal Turing machine, using a finite number of neurons and linear connections.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further, the use of irrational values for weights results in a machine with super-Turing power.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A model's "capacity" property is its ability to model any given function.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is related to the amount of information that can be stored in the network and to the notion of complexity.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Information capacity and the VC dimension are two metrics.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The capacity of a network of standard neurons (not convolutional) can be derived by four rules that derive from considering a neuron as an electrical element.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The information capacity captures the functions that the network can model given any data as input.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC dimension uses the principles of measure theory and finds the maximum capacity under optimal circumstances, given input data in a specific form.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary inputs is half the information capacity of a perceptron.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary points is sometimes referred to as Memory Capacity.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models may not consistently converge on a single solution, because the system may get stuck in a local minima.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, the optimization method used might not guarantee to converge should it begin far from any local minima.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Thirdly, for sufficiently large data or parameters, some methods are impractically slow/expensive.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training may also cross some saddle point that may then prevent access to the solution.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the width of a network approaches infinity, it is well described by its first order Taylor expansion throughout training, and so inherits the convergence behavior of affine models.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] When parameter numbers are small, NNs often fit target functions from low to high frequencies.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This behavior is referred to as spectral bias, or the frequency principle.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This phenomenon is the opposite of the behavior of some well-studied iterative numerical schemes such as the Jacobi method.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deeper neural networks are more biased towards low frequency functions.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Applications that must generalize well to unseen examples, must avoid over-training.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This arises in convoluted or over-specified systems when the network capacity is much larger than needed.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Cross-validation and similar techniques can check for over-training and select appropriate hyperparameters to minimize generalization error.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised neural networks that use a mean squared error (MSE) cost function can use formal statistical methods to determine the confidence of the trained model.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] The MSE on a validation set can be used as an estimate for variance.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This value can then be used to calculate the confidence interval of network output, assuming a normal distribution.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] A confidence analysis made this way is statistically valid as long as the output probability distribution stays the same and the network is not modified.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] By adopting a softmax activation function, a generalization of the logistic function, on the output layer of the neural network (or a softmax component in a component-based network) for categorical target variables, the outputs can be interpreted as posterior probabilities.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is useful in classification as it gives a certainty measure.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks support a broad range of applications in image processing, speech recognition, natural language processing, finance, and medicine.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Because of their ability to model and reproduce nonlinear processes, neural networks have found applications in many disciplines.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to diagnose cancers and to distinguish highly invasive cancer cell lines from less invasive lines using only cell shape data.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to accelerate reliability analysis of infrastructures subject to natural disasters and to predict settling in building foundations.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They are used to mitigate flooding by modelling rainfall-runoff.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used for building black-box models in geoscience: hydrology, ocean modelling and coastal engineering, and geomorphology.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been employed in cybersecurity, with the objective to discriminate between legitimate and malicious activities.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, machine learning has been used for classifying Android malware, for identifying domains belonging to threat actors and for detecting URLs posing a security risk.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Research is underway on penetration testing, for detecting botnets, credit cards frauds, and network intrusions.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been proposed as a tool to solve partial differential equations in physics and simulate the properties of many-body open quantum systems.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In brain research NNs have studied short-term behavior of individual neurons, the dynamics of neural circuitry arise from interactions between individual neurons and how behavior can arise from abstract neural modules that represent complete subsystems.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Studies considered long-and short-term plasticity of neural systems and their relation to learning and memory from the individual neuron to the system level.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs show promise in profiling a user's interests from photos and discovering new stable materials by efficiently predicting the total energy of crystals.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are employed in computer vision tasks such as image classification, object and facial recognition, and image segmentation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They have been applied to automated surveillance medical imaging for diagnosis.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used for speaker identification, speech-to-text, and text-to-speech conversion.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have conquered large vocabulary continuous speech recognition, outperforming traditional techniques.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] These advancements have enabled the development of more accurate and efficient voice-activated systems, enhancing user interfaces in technology products.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In natural language processing, NNs are used for tasks such as text classification, sentiment analysis, machine translation, to answer free-form questions, act as chatbots, and to summarize and analyze texts.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] This has implications for automated customer service, content moderation, and language understanding technologies.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used to model dynamic systems for tasks such as system identification, control design, autonomous vehicles, and optimization.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Large financial institutions use AI to assist with their investment practices.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] BlackRock's AI engine, Aladdin, is used both within the company and by clients to help with investment decisions.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its functions include the use of natural language processing to analyze text such as news, broker reports, and social media feeds.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] It then gauges the sentiment on the companies mentioned and assigns a score.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Banks such as UBS and Deutsche Bank use SQREEM (Sequential Quantum Reduction and Extraction Model) to mine data to develop consumer profiles and match them with wealth management products.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They enhance diagnostic accuracy, especially by interpreting complex medical imaging for early disease detection, and by predicting patient outcomes for personalized treatment planning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] In drug discovery, NNs speed up the identification of potential drug candidates and predict their efficacy and safety, significantly reducing development time and costs.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Additionally, their application in personalized medicine and healthcare data analysis allows tailored therapies and efficient patient care management.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks are widely applied in cybersecurity for anomaly detection, malware classification, and intrusion detection.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] By learning patterns of normal system or network behavior, NNs can identify deviations that indicate malicious activity.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers are used for content creation across numerous industries.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] They can analyze samples and produce outputs that match the style of an artist or musician.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] For instance, DALL-E trained on 650 million pairs of images and texts and can create artworks based on user text.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Companies such as AIVA and Jukedeck have used transformers to create original music.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to create personalized advertisements.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] Film production companies have used NNs to analyze the financial success of a film.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have found uses in video game creation.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs require millions of training samples to become functional.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] As of 2026, training a commercial LLM (GPT, Grok, Gemini) typically required hundreds of thousands of computers, and cost 10s of millions of dollars.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] A central claim of NNs is that they embody new and powerful general principles for processing information.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] However, at root they use statistical long-developed methods.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks require enormous computing resources for training.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] While the brain requires only 20 watts of power, training commercial transformers requires (2026) data centers with hundreds of megawatts.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] From 1991 to 2015, computing power, especially as delivered by GPGPUs (on GPUs), increased around a million-fold, enabling the use of the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neuromorphic engineering or a physical neural network constructed non-von-Neumann chips to directly implement neural networks in circuitry.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, Alphabet introduced custom chips (Tensor Processing Unit).
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] The statistical properties of input data may change over time, a phenomenon known as concept drift or non-stationarity.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Drift can reduce predictive accuracy and lead to unreliable or biased decisions if it is not detected and corrected.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] In practice, this means that the model's accuracy in deployment may differ substantially from levels observed during training.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks are dependent on the quality of their training data; low quality data can lead the model to product poor results.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Biased data produces biased results, requiring trainers to detect and correct them.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, data that underrepresents some demographic groups may prevent cause errors, e.g., in facial recognition and law enforcement.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] In 2018, Amazon scrapped a recruiting tool because the model favored men over women for jobs in software engineering due to the larger number of male workers in the field.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] The system penalized resumes with the word "woman" or the name of a women's college.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] One corrective is to add synthetic data to offset the bias.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are "black box" systems that have complicated understanding of their decision-making processes.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are further vulnerable to adversarial examples ("poison"), that can cause incorrect predictions.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] These concerns have led to increased research in explainable artificial intelligence (XAI), robust machine learning, and hybrid AI approaches that combine neural learning with symbolic reasoning.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Advocates of hybrid models also say that such a mixture can better capture the mechanisms of the human mind.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Progress has included local vs. non-local learning and shallow vs. deep architectures.
[src:keras/artificial-neural-network-p02] Analyzing human thought (a biological neural network) has also proven difficult.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In machine learning, **backpropagation** is a gradient computation method commonly used for training a neural network in computing parameter updates.
[src:keras/backpropagation] It is an efficient application of the chain rule to neural networks.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient of the loss with respect to the network weights for a single input–output example.
[src:keras/backpropagation] It does this by propagating derivatives backward, one layer at a time, from the output layer to the input layer, thereby avoiding redundant chain-rule calculations.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Strictly speaking, the term *backpropagation* refers only to an algorithm for efficiently computing the gradient, not how the gradient is used, but the term is often used loosely to refer to the entire learning algorithm.
[src:keras/backpropagation] This includes changing model parameters in the negative direction of the gradient, such as by stochastic gradient descent, or as an intermediate step in a more complicated optimizer, such as Adaptive Moment Estimation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation had multiple discoveries and partial discoveries, with a tangled history and terminology (see § History).
[src:keras/backpropagation] Some other names for the technique include "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" or "reverse accumulation".
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient in weight space of a feedforward neural network, with respect to a loss function.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In the derivation of backpropagation, other intermediate quantities are used by introducing them as needed below.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Bias terms are not treated specially since they correspond to a weight with a fixed input of 1.
[src:keras/backpropagation] For backpropagation the specific loss function and activation functions do not matter as long as they and their derivatives can be evaluated efficiently.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Traditional activation functions include sigmoid, tanh, ReLU, Swish, Mish, and many others.
[src:keras/backpropagation] For a training set there will be a set of input–output pairs, $\left\{(x_{i},y_{i})\right\}$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] Note the distinction: during model evaluation the weights are fixed while the inputs vary (and the target output may be unknown), and the network ends with the output layer (it does not include the loss function).
[src:keras/backpropagation] During model training the input–output pair is fixed while the weights vary, and the network ends with the loss function.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation computes the gradient for a *fixed* input–output pair $(x_{i},y_{i})$ , where the weights $w_{jk}^{l}$ can vary.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Each individual component of the gradient, $\partial C/\partial w_{jk}^{l},$ can be computed by the chain rule; but doing this separately for each weight is inefficient.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation efficiently computes the gradient by avoiding duplicate calculations and not computing unnecessary intermediate values, by computing the gradient of each layer – specifically the gradient of the weighted *input* of each layer, denoted by $\delta ^{l}$ – from back to front.
[src:keras/backpropagation] First, it avoids duplication because when computing the gradient at layer l , it is unnecessary to recompute all derivatives on later layers $l+1,l+2,\ldots$ each time.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation can be expressed for simple feedforward networks in terms of matrix multiplication, or more generally in terms of the adjoint graph.
[src:keras/backpropagation] To compute this, one starts with the input x and works forward; denote the weighted input of each hidden layer as $z^{l}$ and the output of hidden layer l as the activation $a^{l}$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the activation $a^{l}$ as well as the derivatives $(f^{l})'$ (evaluated at $z^{l}$ ) must be cached for use during the backwards pass.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Note that $\delta ^{l}$ is a vector, of length equal to the number of nodes in level l ; each component is interpreted as the "cost attributable to (the value of) that node".
[src:keras/backpropagation] The factor of $a^{l-1}$ is because the weights $W^{l}$ between level $l-1$ and l affect level l proportionally to the inputs (activations): the inputs are fixed, the weights vary.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The gradients of the weights can thus be computed using a few matrix multiplications for each level; this is backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Multiplying starting from $\nabla _{a^{L}}C$ – propagating the error *backwards* – means that each step simply multiplies a vector ( $\delta ^{l}$ ) by the matrices of weights $(W^{l})^{T}$ and derivatives of activations $(f^{l-1})'$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] By contrast, multiplying forwards, starting from the changes at an earlier layer, means that each multiplication multiplies a *matrix* by a *matrix*.
[src:keras/backpropagation] For more general graphs, and other advanced variations, backpropagation can be understood in terms of automatic differentiation, where backpropagation is a special case of reverse accumulation (or "reverse mode").
[src:keras/backpropagation] The goal of any supervised learning algorithm is to find a function that best maps a set of inputs to their correct output.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The motivation for backpropagation is to train a multi-layered neural network such that it can learn the appropriate internal representations to allow it to learn any arbitrary mapping of input to output.
[src:keras/backpropagation] To understand the mathematical derivation of the backpropagation algorithm, it helps to first develop some intuition about the relationship between the actual output of a neuron and the correct output for a particular training example.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Consider a simple neural network with two input units, one output unit and no hidden units, and in which each neuron uses a linear output (unlike most work on neural networks, in which mapping from inputs to outputs is non-linear) that is the weighted sum of its input.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Initially, before training, the weights will be set randomly.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Then the neuron learns from training examples, which in this case consist of a set of tuples $(x_{1},x_{2},t)$ where $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are the inputs to the network and t is the correct output (the output the network should produce given those inputs, when it has been trained).
[src:keras/backpropagation] The initial network, given $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ , will compute an output y that likely differs from t (given random weights).
[src:keras/backpropagation] A loss function $L(t,y)$ is used for measuring the discrepancy between the target output t and the computed output y.
[src:keras/backpropagation] For regression analysis problems the squared error can be used as a loss function, for classification the categorical cross-entropy can be used.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Consider the network on a single training case: $(1,1,0)$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] Thus, the input $x_{1}$ and $x_{2}$ are 1 and 1 respectively and the correct output, t is 0.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Now if the relation is plotted between the network's output y on the horizontal axis and the error E on the vertical axis, the result is a parabola.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The minimum of the parabola corresponds to the output y which minimizes the error E.
[src:keras/backpropagation] For a single training case, the minimum also touches the horizontal axis, which means the error will be zero and the network can produce an output y that exactly matches the target output t.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Therefore, the problem of mapping inputs to outputs can be reduced to an optimization problem of finding a function that will produce the minimal error.
[src:keras/backpropagation] where $w_{1}$ and $w_{2}$ are the weights on the connection from the input units to the output unit.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Therefore, the error also depends on the incoming weights to the neuron, which is ultimately what needs to be changed in the network to enable learning.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Then, the loss function E takes the form of a parabolic cylinder with its base directed along $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] Since all sets of weights that satisfy $w_{1}=-w_{2}$ minimize the loss function, in this case additional constraints are required to converge to a unique solution.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Additional constraints could either be generated by setting specific conditions to the weights, or by injecting additional training data.
[src:keras/backpropagation] One commonly used algorithm to find the set of weights that minimizes the error is gradient descent.
[src:keras/backpropagation] By backpropagation, the steepest descent direction is calculated of the loss function versus the present synaptic weights.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Then, the weights can be modified along the steepest descent direction, and the error is minimized in an efficient way.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The gradient descent method involves calculating the derivative of the loss function with respect to the weights of the network.
[src:keras/backpropagation] This is normally done using backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] is the actual output of the output neuron.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In this section, the order of the weight indexes are reversed relative to the prior section: $w_{ij}$ is weight from the i th to the j th unit.
[src:keras/backpropagation] where the activation function $\varphi$ is non-linear and differentiable over the activation region (the ReLU is not differentiable at one point).
[src:keras/backpropagation] The input ${\text{net}}_{j}$ to a neuron is the weighted sum of outputs $o_{k}$ of previous neurons.
[src:keras/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, the $o_{k}$ of the input layer are simply the inputs $x_{k}$ to the network.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The number of input units to the neuron is n .
[src:keras/backpropagation] The variable $w_{kj}$ denotes the weight between neuron k of the previous layer and neuron j of the current layer.
[src:keras/backpropagation] If the neuron is in the first layer after the input layer, $o_{i}$ is just $x_{i}$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] This is the reason why backpropagation requires that the activation function be differentiable.
[src:keras/backpropagation] However, if j is in an arbitrary inner layer of the network, finding the derivative E with respect to $o_{j}$ is less obvious.
[src:keras/backpropagation] To update the weight $w_{ij}$ using gradient descent, one must choose a learning rate, $\eta >0$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] The change in weight needs to reflect the impact on E of an increase or decrease in $w_{ij}$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] If ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}>0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ increases E ; conversely, if ${\frac {\partial E}{\partial w_{ij}}}<0$ , an increase in $w_{ij}$ decreases E .
[src:keras/backpropagation] The new $\Delta w_{ij}$ is added to the old weight, and the product of the learning rate and the gradient, multiplied by $-1$ guarantees that $w_{ij}$ changes in a way that always decreases E .
[src:keras/backpropagation] Using a Hessian matrix of second-order derivatives of the error function, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm often converges faster than first-order gradient descent, especially when the topology of the error function is complicated.
[src:keras/backpropagation] It may also find solutions in smaller node counts for which other methods might not converge.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The Hessian can be approximated by the Fisher information matrix.
[src:keras/backpropagation] As an example, consider a simple feedforward network.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Arbitrary-order derivatives in arbitrary computational graphs can be computed with backpropagation, but with more complex expressions for higher orders.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The loss function is a function that maps values of one or more variables onto a real number intuitively representing some "cost" associated with those values.
[src:keras/backpropagation] For backpropagation, the loss function calculates the difference between the network output and its expected output, after a training example has propagated through the network.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The mathematical expression of the loss function must fulfill two conditions in order for it to be possibly used in backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The first is that it can be written as an average ${\textstyle E={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{x}E_{x}}$ over error functions ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ , for ${\textstyle n}$ individual training examples, ${\textstyle x}$ .
[src:keras/backpropagation] The reason for this assumption is that the backpropagation algorithm calculates the gradient of the error function for a single training example, which needs to be generalized to the overall error function.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The second assumption is that it can be written as a function of the outputs from the neural network.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Select an error function $E(y,y')$ measuring the difference between two outputs.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Backpropagation had been derived repeatedly, as it is essentially an efficient application of the chain rule (first written down by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1676) to neural networks.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The terminology "back-propagating error correction" was introduced in 1962 by Frank Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In any case, he only studied neurons whose outputs were discrete levels, which only had zero derivatives, making backpropagation impossible.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Precursors to backpropagation appeared in optimal control theory since 1950s.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Yann LeCun et al credits 1950s work by Pontryagin and others in optimal control theory, especially the adjoint state method, for being a continuous-time version of backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Hecht-Nielsen credits the Robbins–Monro algorithm (1951) and Arthur Bryson and Yu-Chi Ho's *Applied Optimal Control* (1969) as presages of backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1962, Stuart Dreyfus published a simpler derivation based only on the chain rule.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1973, he adapted parameters of controllers in proportion to error gradients.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Unlike modern backpropagation, these precursors used standard Jacobian matrix calculations from one stage to the previous one, neither addressing direct links across several stages nor potential additional efficiency gains due to network sparsity.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The ADALINE (1960) learning algorithm was gradient descent with a squared error loss for a single layer.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The first multilayer perceptron (MLP) with more than one layer trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The MLP had 5 layers, with 2 learnable layers, and it learned to classify patterns not linearly separable.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Modern backpropagation was first published by Seppo Linnainmaa as "reverse mode of automatic differentiation" (1970) for discrete connected networks of nested differentiable functions.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1982, Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to MLPs in the way that has become standard.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Werbos described how he developed backpropagation in an interview.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1971, during his PhD work, he developed backpropagation to mathematicize Freud's "flow of psychic energy".
[src:keras/backpropagation] He faced repeated difficulty in publishing the work, only managing in 1981.
[src:keras/backpropagation] He also claimed that "the first practical application of back-propagation was for estimating a dynamic model to predict nationalism and social communications in 1974" by him.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Rumelhart independently developed backpropagation and taught the algorithm to others in his research circle.
[src:keras/backpropagation] He did not cite previous work as he was unaware of them.
[src:keras/backpropagation] He published the algorithm first in a 1985 paper, then in a 1986 *Nature* paper an experimental analysis of the technique.
[src:keras/backpropagation] These papers became highly cited, contributed to the popularization of backpropagation, and coincided with the resurging research interest in neural networks during the 1980s.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1985, the method was also described by David Parker.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Yann LeCun proposed an alternative form of backpropagation for neural networks in his PhD thesis in 1987.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Gradient descent took a considerable amount of time to reach acceptance.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Some early objections were: there were no guarantees that gradient descent could reach a global minimum, only local minimum; neurons were "known" by physiologists as making discrete signals (0/1), not continuous ones, and with discrete signals, there is no gradient to take.
[src:keras/backpropagation] See the interview with Geoffrey Hinton, who was awarded the 2024 Nobel Prize in Physics for his contributions to the field.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Contributing to the acceptance were several applications in training neural networks via backpropagation, sometimes achieving popularity outside the research circles.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1987, NETtalk learned to convert English text into pronunciation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Sejnowski tried training it with both backpropagation and Boltzmann machine, but found the backpropagation significantly faster, so he used it for the final NETtalk.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The NETtalk program became a popular success, appearing on the *Today* show.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Pomerleau published ALVINN, a neural network trained to drive autonomously using backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] The LeNet was published in 1989 to recognize handwritten zip codes.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1992, TD-Gammon achieved top human level play in backgammon.
[src:keras/backpropagation] It was a reinforcement learning agent with a neural network with two layers, trained by backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 1993, Eric Wan won an international pattern recognition contest through backpropagation.
[src:keras/backpropagation] During the 2000s it fell out of favour, but returned in the 2010s, benefiting from cheap, powerful GPU-based computing systems.
[src:keras/backpropagation] Error backpropagation has been suggested to explain human brain event-related potential (ERP) components like the N400 and P600.
[src:keras/backpropagation] In 2023, a backpropagation algorithm was implemented on a photonic processor by a team at Stanford University.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:keras/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:keras/keras] The name 'Keras' derives from the Ancient Greek word κέρας (Keras) meaning 'horn'.
[src:keras/keras] Designed to enable fast experimentation with deep neural networks, Keras focuses on being user-friendly, modular, and extensible.
[src:keras/keras] It was developed as part of the research effort of project ONEIROS (Open-ended Neuro-Electronic Intelligent Robot Operating System), and its primary author and maintainer is François Chollet, who was a Google engineer until leaving the company in 2024.
[src:keras/keras] Chollet is also the author of the Xception deep neural network model.
[src:keras/keras] Up until version 2.3, Keras supported multiple backends, including TensorFlow, Microsoft Cognitive Toolkit, Theano, and PlaidML.
[src:keras/keras] From version 2.4 up until version 3.0, only TensorFlow was supported.
[src:keras/keras] Starting with version 3.0 (as well as its preview version, Keras Core), however, Keras has become multi-backend again, supporting TensorFlow, JAX, and PyTorch.
[src:keras/keras] Keras contains numerous implementations of commonly used neural-network building blocks such as layers, objectives, activation functions, optimizers, and a host of tools for working with image and text data to simplify programming for deep neural networks.
[src:keras/keras] The code is hosted on GitHub, and community support forums include the GitHub issues page.
[src:keras/keras] In addition to standard neural networks, Keras has support for convolutional and recurrent neural networks.
[src:keras/keras] It supports other common utility layers like dropout, batch normalization, and pooling.
[src:keras/keras] Keras allows users to produce deep models on smartphones (iOS and Android), on the web, or on the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:keras/keras] It also allows use of distributed training of deep-learning models on clusters of graphics processing units (GPU) and tensor processing units (TPU).
[src:keras/tensorflow] It was developed by the Google Brain team for Google's internal use in research and production.
[src:keras/tensorflow] The initial version was released under the Apache License 2.0 in 2015.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google released an updated version, TensorFlow 2.0, in September 2019.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow can be used in a wide variety of programming languages, including Python, JavaScript, C++, and Java, facilitating its use in a range of applications in many sectors.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Starting in 2011, Google Brain built DistBelief as a proprietary machine learning system based on deep learning neural networks.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Its use grew rapidly across diverse Alphabet companies in both research and commercial applications.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google assigned multiple computer scientists, including Jeff Dean, to simplify and refactor the codebase of DistBelief into a faster, more robust application-grade library, which became TensorFlow.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In 2009, the team, led by Geoffrey Hinton, had implemented generalized backpropagation and other improvements, which allowed generation of neural networks with substantially higher accuracy, for instance a 25% reduction in errors in speech recognition.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow is Google Brain's second-generation system.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Version 1.0.0 was released on February 11, 2017.
[src:keras/tensorflow] While the reference implementation runs on single devices, TensorFlow can run on multiple CPUs and GPUs (with optional CUDA and SYCL extensions for general-purpose computing on graphics processing units).
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow is available on 64-bit Linux, macOS, Windows, and mobile computing platforms including Android and iOS.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Its flexible architecture allows for easy deployment of computation across a variety of platforms (CPUs, GPUs, TPUs), and from desktops to clusters of servers to mobile and edge devices.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow computations are expressed as stateful dataflow graphs.
[src:keras/tensorflow] The name TensorFlow derives from the operations that such neural networks perform on multidimensional data arrays, which are referred to as *tensors*.
[src:keras/tensorflow] During the Google I/O Conference in June 2016, Jeff Dean stated that 1,500 repositories on GitHub mentioned TensorFlow, of which only 5 were from Google.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In March 2018, Google announced TensorFlow.js version 1.0 for machine learning in JavaScript.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In Jan 2019, Google announced TensorFlow 2.0.
[src:keras/tensorflow] It became officially available in September 2019.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In May 2019, Google announced TensorFlow Graphics for deep learning in computer graphics.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In May 2016, Google announced its Tensor processing unit (TPU), an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC, a hardware chip) built specifically for machine learning and tailored for TensorFlow.
[src:keras/tensorflow] A TPU is a programmable AI accelerator designed to provide high throughput of low-precision arithmetic (e.g., 8-bit), and oriented toward using or running models rather than training them.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google announced they had been running TPUs inside their data centers for more than a year, and had found them to deliver an order of magnitude better-optimized performance per watt for machine learning.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In May 2017, Google announced the second-generation, as well as the availability of the TPUs in Google Compute Engine.
[src:keras/tensorflow] The second-generation TPUs deliver up to 180 teraflops of performance, and when organized into clusters of 64 TPUs, provide up to 11.5 petaflops.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In May 2018, Google announced the third-generation TPUs delivering up to 420 teraflops of performance and 128 GB high bandwidth memory (HBM).
[src:keras/tensorflow] Cloud TPU v3 Pods offer 100+ petaflops of performance and 32 TB HBM.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In February 2018, Google announced that they were making TPUs available in beta on the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In July 2018, the Edge TPU was announced.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Edge TPU is Google's purpose-built ASIC chip designed to run TensorFlow Lite machine learning (ML) models on small client computing devices such as smartphones known as edge computing.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In May 2017, Google announced TensorFlow Lite as a software stack to support machine learning models for mobile and embedded devices, and in November 2017, provided the developer preview.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In January 2019, the TensorFlow team released a developer preview of the mobile GPU inference engine with OpenGL ES 3.1 Compute Shaders on Android devices and Metal Compute Shaders on iOS devices.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In May 2019, Google announced that their TensorFlow Lite Micro (also known as TensorFlow Lite for Microcontrollers) and ARM's uTensor would be merging.
[src:keras/tensorflow] As TensorFlow's market share among research papers was declining to the advantage of PyTorch, the TensorFlow Team announced a release of a new major version of the library in September 2019.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow 2.0 introduced many changes, the most significant being TensorFlow eager, which changed the automatic differentiation scheme from the static computational graph to the "Define-by-Run" scheme originally made popular by Chainer and later PyTorch.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Other major changes included removal of old libraries, cross-compatibility between trained models on different versions of TensorFlow, and significant improvements to the performance on GPU.
[src:keras/tensorflow] AutoDifferentiation is the process of automatically calculating the gradient vector of a model with respect to each of its parameters.
[src:keras/tensorflow] With this feature, TensorFlow can automatically compute the gradients for the parameters in a model, which is useful to algorithms such as backpropagation which require gradients to optimize performance.
[src:keras/tensorflow] To do so, the framework must keep track of the order of operations done to the input Tensors in a model, and then compute the gradients with respect to the appropriate parameters.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow includes an "eager execution" mode, which means that operations are evaluated immediately as opposed to being added to a computational graph which is executed later.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Code executed eagerly can be examined step-by step-through a debugger, since data is augmented at each line of code rather than later in a computational graph.
[src:keras/tensorflow] This execution paradigm is considered to be easier to debug because of its step by step transparency.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In both eager and graph executions, TensorFlow provides an API for distributing computation across multiple devices with various distribution strategies.
[src:keras/tensorflow] This distributed computing can often speed up the execution of training and evaluating of TensorFlow models and is a common practice in the field of AI.
[src:keras/tensorflow] To train and assess models, TensorFlow provides a set of loss functions (also known as cost functions).
[src:keras/tensorflow] Some popular examples include mean squared error (MSE) and binary cross entropy (BCE).
[src:keras/tensorflow] In order to assess the performance of machine learning models, TensorFlow gives API access to commonly used metrics.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Examples include various accuracy metrics (binary, categorical, sparse categorical) along with other metrics such as Precision, Recall, and Intersection-over-Union (IoU).
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow.nn is a module for executing primitive neural network operations on models.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Some of these operations include variations of convolutions (1/2/3D, Atrous, depthwise), activation functions (Softmax, RELU, GELU, Sigmoid, etc.) and their variations, and other operations (max-pooling, bias-add, etc.).
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow offers a set of optimizers for training neural networks, including ADAM, ADAGRAD, and Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD).
[src:keras/tensorflow] When training a model, different optimizers offer different modes of parameter tuning, often affecting a model's convergence and performance.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow serves as a core platform and library for machine learning.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow's APIs use Keras to allow users to make their own machine-learning models.
[src:keras/tensorflow] In addition to building and training their model, TensorFlow can also help load the data to train the model, and deploy it using TensorFlow Serving.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow provides a stable Python Application Program Interface (API), as well as APIs without backwards compatibility guarantee for JavaScript, C++, and Java.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Third-party language binding packages are also available for C#, Haskell, Julia, MATLAB, Object Pascal, R, Scala, Rust, OCaml, and Crystal.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Bindings that are now archived and unsupported include Go and Swift.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow also has a library for machine learning in JavaScript.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Using the provided JavaScript APIs, TensorFlow.js allows users to use either Tensorflow.js models or converted models from TensorFlow or TFLite, retrain the given models, and run on the web.
[src:keras/tensorflow] LiteRT, formerly known as TensorFlow Lite, has APIs for mobile apps or embedded devices to generate and deploy TensorFlow models.
[src:keras/tensorflow] These models are compressed and optimized in order to be more efficient and have a higher performance on smaller capacity devices.
[src:keras/tensorflow] LiteRT uses FlatBuffers as the data serialization format for network models, eschewing the Protocol Buffers format used by standard TensorFlow models.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TFX) provides numerous components to perform all the operations needed for end-to-end production.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Components include loading, validating, and transforming data, tuning, training, and evaluating the machine learning model, and pushing the model itself into production.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Numpy is one of the most popular Python data libraries, and TensorFlow offers integration and compatibility with its data structures.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Numpy NDarrays, the library's native datatype, are automatically converted to TensorFlow Tensors in TF operations; the same is also true vice versa.
[src:keras/tensorflow] This allows for the two libraries to work in unison without requiring the user to write explicit data conversions.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Moreover, the integration extends to memory optimization by having TF Tensors share the underlying memory representations of Numpy NDarrays whenever possible.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow also offers a variety of libraries and extensions to advance and extend the models and methods used.
[src:keras/tensorflow] For example, TensorFlow Recommenders and TensorFlow Graphics are libraries for their respective functional.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Other add-ons, libraries, and frameworks include TensorFlow Model Optimization, TensorFlow Probability, TensorFlow Quantum, and TensorFlow Decision Forests.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google also released Collaboratory, a TensorFlow Jupyter notebook environment that does not require any setup.
[src:keras/tensorflow] It runs on Google Cloud and allows users free access to GPUs and the ability to store and share notebooks on Google Drive.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google JAX is a machine learning framework for transforming numerical functions.
[src:keras/tensorflow] It is described as bringing together a modified version of autograd (automatic obtaining of the gradient function through differentiation of a function) and TensorFlow's XLA (Accelerated Linear Algebra).
[src:keras/tensorflow] It is designed to follow the structure and workflow of NumPy as closely as possible and works with TensorFlow as well as other frameworks such as PyTorch.
[src:keras/tensorflow] GE Healthcare used TensorFlow to increase the speed and accuracy of MRIs in identifying specific body parts.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google used TensorFlow to create DermAssist, a free mobile application that allows users to take pictures of their skin and identify potential health complications.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Sinovation Ventures used TensorFlow to identify and classify eye diseases from optical coherence tomography (OCT) scans.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Twitter implemented TensorFlow to rank tweets by importance for a given user, and changed their platform to show tweets in order of this ranking.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Previously, tweets were simply shown in reverse chronological order.
[src:keras/tensorflow] The photo sharing app VSCO used TensorFlow to help suggest custom filters for photos.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Google officially released RankBrain on October 26, 2015, backed by TensorFlow.
[src:keras/tensorflow] InSpace, a virtual learning platform, used TensorFlow to filter out toxic chat messages in classrooms.
[src:keras/tensorflow] Liulishuo, an online English learning platform, utilized TensorFlow to create an adaptive curriculum for each student.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow was used to assess the current abilities of students and also helped decide which content to show based on those capabilities.
[src:keras/tensorflow] The e-commerce platform Carousell used TensorFlow to provide personalized recommendations for customers.
[src:keras/tensorflow] The cosmetics company ModiFace used TensorFlow to create an augmented reality experience for customers to test various shades of make-up on their face.
[src:keras/tensorflow] TensorFlow is the foundation for the automated image-captioning software DeepDream.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:keras/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:keras/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:keras/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
